<section xml:id="sec-derivative-implicit" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Implicit Differentiation</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Students should know when they should apply implicit differentiation.</li>
      <li>
        Students should be able to apply the implicit differentiation technique in simple to slightly complicated problems,
        including those requiring the use of the product, quotient, or chain rule.
      </li>
      <li>Students should be able to interpret the results of implicit differentiation as the slope of a curve.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <p>
    In earlier sections, we found tangent lines and rates of change by differentiating functions written in the form
    <m>y=f(x)</m>. However, many important curves are not given as explicit functions of <m>x</m>.
    Instead, they are described by equations that relate <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> implicitly.
    In this section, we develop a technique called <emph>implicit differentiation</emph> that allows us to
    compute derivatives directly from such equations.
  </p>

<subsection xml:id="ssec-explicit-vs-implicit">
    <title>Explicit versus Implicit Functions</title>

    <p>
      Consider the circle defined by the equation <m>x^2+y^2=25</m>.
      If we wish to find the slope of the tangent line at the point <m>(3,4)</m>,
      we immediately face a difficulty: there is no function specified in the form <m>y=f(x)</m>.


      <sidebyside width="60%">
        <figure xml:id="fig-implicit-circle-tangent">
  <caption>
    Tangent line to the circle <m>x^2 + y^2 = 25</m> at the point <m>(3,4)</m>.
  </caption>

  <image source="images/impDiff01.PNG" width="60%">
    <shortdescription>
      A coordinate plane showing the circle defined by x squared plus y squared equals 25.
      The circle is centered at the origin with radius 5.
      A dashed line represents the tangent line at the point (3,4),
      touching the circle at exactly one point.
      The point of tangency is marked, and the tangent line slopes downward to the right.
    </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </p>

    <p>
      One possible approach is to make the equation explicit by solving for <m>y</m>. Let's consider this method first
    </p>

<example xml:id="ex-explicit-circle-tangent">

  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the equation of the tangent line to the circle
      <m>x^2+y^2=25</m> at the point <m>(3,4)</m> by first solving for
      <m>y=f(x)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We begin by solving the equation of the circle for <m>y</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      y = \pm\sqrt{25-x^2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This shows that the circle is the union of two function graphs.
      Since the point <m>(3,4)</m> lies on the upper semicircle, we use
      <m>y=\sqrt{25-x^2}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Differentiate using the Chain Rule:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{dy}{dx}
      =
      \frac{d}{dx}(25-x^2)^{1/2}
      =
      \frac12(25-x^2)^{-1/2}(-2x)
      =
      -\frac{x}{\sqrt{25-x^2}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Evaluating at <m>x=3</m> gives
      <m>\frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac34</m>.
      Using point-slope form, the equation of the tangent line is
    </p>

    <me>
      y = -\frac34(x-3)+4.
    </me>
  </solution>
</example>


<remark xml:id="rem-implicit-motivation">
  <p>
    While solving an equation for <m>y</m> can sometimes allow us to apply standard
    differentiation rules, this approach is often inconvenient and may even be
    impossible. In many equations, even relatively simple ones, such as <m>e^{y}=x+y</m>, the variable <m>y</m>
    appears in multiple locations and cannot be isolated as an explicit function
    of <m>x</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Implicit differentiation avoids this difficulty by treating <m>y</m> as a
    function of <m>x</m> and differentiating both sides of the equation directly,
    using the Chain Rule wherever <m>y</m> appears.
  </p>
</remark>
  </subsection>

   <subsection xml:id="ssec-implicit-diff-circle">
    <title>Implicit Differentiation in Action</title>

    <p>
      Instead of solving for <m>y</m>, we assume that <m>y=y(x)</m> is an unknown function of <m>x</m>
      that satisfies the equation <m>x^2+y^2=25</m>.
      We then differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
        \frac{d}{dx}(x^2+y^2) &amp;=&amp; \frac{d}{dx}(25) \\[0.6em]
        2x + 2y\frac{dy}{dx} &amp;=&amp; 0.
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      The derivative of <m>y^2</m> requires the Chain Rule, since <m>y</m> is itself a function of <m>x</m>.
      Solving for <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> gives
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{x}{y}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This formula applies to both the upper and lower semicircles.
      At <m>(3,4)</m>, the slope is <m>-\frac34</m>,
      while at <m>(3,-4)</m> the slope is <m>\frac34</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-second-derivative-implicit">
    <title>Higher Derivatives via Implicit Differentiation</title>

    <p>
      Implicit differentiation can also be used to compute higher derivatives.
      Starting from
      <m>\frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac{x}{y}</m>,
      we differentiate again with respect to <m>x</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      y''(x)
      =
      \left(-\frac{x}{y}\right)'
      =
      -\frac{y - x\frac{dy}{dx}}{y^2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Substituting <m>\frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac{x}{y}</m> and using <m>x^2+y^2=25</m> yields
    </p>

    <me>
      y''(x) = -\frac{25}{y^3}.
    </me>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-implicit-non-solvable">
    <title>When Explicit Formulas Are Not Practical</title>

    <p>
      Some curves cannot be easily written as explicit functions.
      An important example is the <emph>Folium of Descartes</emph>, defined by
      <m>x^3+y^3=9xy</m>.
      Over certain intervals, this curve consists of multiple overlapping function graphs.
    </p>

    <p>
      Even in such cases, implicit differentiation works smoothly.
      Assuming <m>y=y(x)</m> and differentiating both sides gives
    </p>

    <me>
      3x^2 + 3y^2\frac{dy}{dx} = 9y + 9x\frac{dy}{dx}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solving for <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> yields
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{9y - 3x^2}{3y^2 - 9x}.
    </me>

    <p>
      At the point <m>(2,4)</m>, the slope of the tangent line is <m>\frac45</m>,
      giving the tangent line
      <m>y=\frac45(x-2)+4</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-implicit-method">
    <title>A General Method for Implicit Differentiation</title>

    <p>
      When given an equation involving <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, proceed as follows:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        Assume <m>x</m> is the independent variable and <m>y=y(x)</m>.
        Differentiate both sides of the equation with respect to <m>x</m>,
        using the Chain Rule whenever a derivative of <m>y</m> appears.
      </li>
      <li>
        Solve the resulting equation for <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
        To find a specific slope at <m>x=a</m>, substitute the known values of
        <m>x=a</m> and <m>y=y(a)</m>.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="implicit-diff-definition">
    <title>Key Idea: Implicit Differentiation</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-implicit-differentiation">
      <title>Implicit Differentiation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <term>Implicit differentiation</term> consists of differentiating both sides of an equation with respect to <m>x</m>
          and then solving the resulting equation for <m>y'</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the examples and exercises of this section, it is assumed that the given equation determines <m>y</m> implicitly
          as a differentiable function of <m>x</m>, so that implicit differentiation applies.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <remark xml:id="rem-implicit-why">
      <p>
        The key feature is that <m>y</m> depends on <m>x</m>, even if the equation does not explicitly solve for <m>y</m>.
        So whenever you differentiate an expression containing <m>y</m>, you must use the Chain Rule and include a factor of <m>y'</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="implicit-diff-straightforward">
    <title>Straightforward Examples</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-implicit-ln">
      <title>Implicit Differentiation with a Logarithm</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given the equation <m>x\ln(y)+y^2=4x</m>, find <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> using implicit differentiation.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>. The left side requires the Product Rule on <m>x\ln(y)</m>
          and the Chain Rule on <m>\ln(y)</m> and <m>y^2</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(x\ln(y)\bigr)+\frac{d}{dx}\bigl(y^2\bigr)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}(4x)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle \Bigl(1\cdot \ln(y)+x\cdot \frac{1}{y}\,y'\Bigr)+2y\,y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 4.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Now solve for <m>y'</m> by collecting terms with <m>y'</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{x}{y}\,y'+2y\,y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 4-\ln(y)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'\left(\frac{x}{y}+2y\right)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 4-\ln(y)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{4-\ln(y)}{\frac{x}{y}+2y}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          A common simplification is to multiply top and bottom by <m>y</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle y'=\frac{y(4-\ln(y))}{x+2y^2}.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-implicit-astroid-like">
      <title>Horizontal Tangent in the First Quadrant</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>y'</m> if <m>y^3+x^3=6xy</m>. At what point in the first quadrant is the tangent line to this curve horizontal?
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>. On the right side, use the Product Rule on <m>6xy</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}(y^3)+\frac{d}{dx}(x^3)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}(6xy)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle 3y^2y'+3x^2
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 6\bigl(xy'+y\bigr)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle 3y^2y'+3x^2
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 6xy'+6y.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Solve for <m>y'</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle 3y^2y'-6xy'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 6y-3x^2
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'(3y^2-6x)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 3(2y-x^2)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{3(2y-x^2)}{3y^2-6x}
\ =\ \frac{2y-x^2}{y^2-2x}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          A horizontal tangent occurs when <m>\displaystyle y'=0</m>, which requires the numerator to be zero (and the denominator nonzero):
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle 2y-x^2=0 \quad\Longrightarrow\quad y=\frac{x^2}{2}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Substitute <m>\displaystyle y=\frac{x^2}{2}</m> into the original equation <m>y^3+x^3=6xy</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \left(\frac{x^2}{2}\right)^3+x^3
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 6x\left(\frac{x^2}{2}\right)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle \frac{x^6}{8}+x^3
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 3x^3
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle \frac{x^6}{8}
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 2x^3.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          In the first quadrant, <m>x&gt;0</m>, so divide by <m>x^3</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{x^3}{8}
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 2
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle x^3
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 16
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle x
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \sqrt[3]{16}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Then
          <m>\displaystyle y=\frac{x^2}{2}=\frac{(\sqrt[3]{16})^2}{2}=\frac{\sqrt[3]{256}}{2}</m>.
          So the point in the first quadrant where the tangent is horizontal is
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle \left(\sqrt[3]{16},\,\frac{(\sqrt[3]{16})^2}{2}\right).
        </me>

        <p>
          (This point is valid as long as <m>y^2-2x\neq 0</m>, which you can check holds here.)
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-implicit-tangent-line">
      <title>Tangent Line from an Implicit Equation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find an equation of the tangent line to the curve <m>y e^{\sin x}=x\cos y</m> at the point <m>(0,0)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>. Use the Product Rule on both sides.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(ye^{\sin x}\bigr)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(x\cos y\bigr)
\\[1.4em]
\displaystyle y'e^{\sin x}+y\cdot e^{\sin x}\cdot(\cos x)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 1\cdot \cos y + x\cdot \frac{d}{dx}(\cos y)
\\[1.4em]
\displaystyle y'e^{\sin x}+y e^{\sin x}\cos x
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \cos y + x\cdot\bigl(-\sin y\bigr)\,y'.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Now substitute <m>(x,y)=(0,0)</m>. Note <m>\sin(0)=0</m>, <m>e^0=1</m>, <m>\cos(0)=1</m>, and <m>\sin(0)=0</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle y'(1)+0
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 1+0
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 1.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          The slope at <m>(0,0)</m> is 1, so the tangent line is
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle y=x.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="implicit-diff-conceptual">
    <title>More Challenging and Conceptual Problems</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-intercepts-tangent">
      <title>Intercept Form and a Constant Sum</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the sum of the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-intercepts of any tangent line to the curve
          <m>\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{y}=\sqrt{c}</m> is equal to <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Differentiate implicitly:
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(\sqrt{x}\bigr)+\frac{d}{dx}\bigl(\sqrt{y}\bigr)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(\sqrt{c}\bigr)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}+\frac{1}{2\sqrt{y}}\,y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 0
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle -\frac{\sqrt{y}}{\sqrt{x}}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          At a point <m>(a,b)</m> on the curve, the slope is
          <m>\displaystyle m=-\frac{\sqrt{b}}{\sqrt{a}}</m>.
          The tangent line is
          <m>\displaystyle y-b=m(x-a)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Find the intercepts. The <m>x</m>-intercept occurs when <m>y=0</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle 0-b
\amp=\amp \displaystyle m(x-a)
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle x
\amp=\amp \displaystyle a-\frac{b}{m}
\ =\ a+b\frac{\sqrt{a}}{\sqrt{b}}
\ =\ a+\sqrt{ab}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          So the <m>x</m>-intercept is <m>a+\sqrt{ab}</m>. The <m>y</m>-intercept occurs when <m>x=0</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle y-b
\amp=\amp \displaystyle m(0-a)
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle y
\amp=\amp \displaystyle b-am
\ =\ b+a\frac{\sqrt{b}}{\sqrt{a}}
\ =\ b+\sqrt{ab}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Thus the sum of intercepts is
          <m>\displaystyle (a+\sqrt{ab})+(b+\sqrt{ab})=a+b+2\sqrt{ab}=(\sqrt{a}+\sqrt{b})^2</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Since <m>(a,b)</m> lies on <m>\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{y}=\sqrt{c}</m>, we have <m>\sqrt{a}+\sqrt{b}=\sqrt{c}</m>, so
          <m>(\sqrt{a}+\sqrt{b})^2=c</m>. Therefore the sum of the intercepts is always <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-ellipse-parallel">
      <title>Parallel Tangents on an Ellipse</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the ellipse given by <m>x^2-xy+y^2=3</m>. Find the points where the ellipse crosses the <m>x</m>-axis
          and show that the tangent lines at these points are parallel.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Points on the <m>x</m>-axis have <m>y=0</m>. Substitute into the equation:
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle x^2-x(0)+0^2
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 3
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle x^2
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 3
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle x
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \pm \sqrt{3}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          So the ellipse crosses the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>(\sqrt{3},0)</m> and <m>(-\sqrt{3},0)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Differentiate implicitly:
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}(x^2)-\frac{d}{dx}(xy)+\frac{d}{dx}(y^2)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}(3)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle 2x-\bigl(xy'+y\bigr)+2y\,y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 0
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle 2x-y-xy'+2y\,y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 0
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'(-x+2y)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle y-2x
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{y-2x}{-x+2y}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          At points on the <m>x</m>-axis, <m>y=0</m>, so
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle y'=\frac{-2x}{-x}=2
          \qquad (x\neq 0).
        </me>

        <p>
          In particular, the slope at both <m>(\sqrt{3},0)</m> and <m>(-\sqrt{3},0)</m> is 2, so the tangent lines are parallel.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-when-implicit-needed">
      <title>When Do We Need Implicit Differentiation?</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain how to determine when implicit differentiation is needed to find <m>y'</m>, as opposed to using
          the standard differentiation methods covered earlier. Provide an example where implicit differentiation is required
          and one where it is not.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Implicit differentiation is needed when <m>y</m> is not given explicitly as a function of <m>x</m>, or when the equation
          mixes <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> in a way that makes solving for <m>y</m> difficult or undesirable. In these cases, we treat <m>y</m>
          as a function of <m>x</m> and differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>, remembering that derivatives of expressions involving
          <m>y</m> must include a factor of <m>y'</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          For example, the equation <m>x^2+y^2=25</m> defines a circle. Solving for <m>y</m> gives
          <m>y=\pm\sqrt{25-x^2}</m>, which is possible but splits into two functions. Implicit differentiation gives
          <m>\displaystyle 2x+2y\,y'=0</m>, so <m>\displaystyle y'=-\frac{x}{y}</m>, which works on the whole circle
          (except where <m>y=0</m>).
        </p>

        <p>
          On the other hand, if <m>y</m> is already given explicitly, such as <m>y=(x^2+1)^5</m>, then standard differentiation rules apply directly
          and there is no need for implicit differentiation. In this example, the Chain Rule gives
          <m>\displaystyle y'=5(x^2+1)^4\cdot 2x</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-geom-meaning-slope">
      <title>Geometric Meaning of <m>y'=5</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A student uses implicit differentiation on a curve and finds that <m>y'=5</m> at the point <m>(x,y)=(1,2)</m>.
          Explain the geometric meaning of this result as it relates to the graph of the curve.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The derivative <m>y'=5</m> at <m>(1,2)</m> means that the tangent line to the curve at that point has slope 5.
          Geometrically, the curve is increasing at <m>(1,2)</m>, and near that point the graph rises about 5 units vertically
          for every 1 unit horizontally (using the usual interpretation of slope).
        </p>

        <p>
          Equivalently, if we zoom in close enough around <m>(1,2)</m>, the curve looks nearly like the tangent line, and that tangent line has equation


        <me>
          \displaystyle y-2=5(x-1).
        </me>
                </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

